and gathering. Potentiating non-exclusionary belonging, black religion is anarchic, mystical, and experimental: it reveals alternative relationalities and visions of matter that can counter capitalism’s extractive, individualistic, and imperialist ideology. By enacting a black study of religion, Carter elucidates the violence of religion as the violence of modern life while also opening an alternate praxis of the sacred.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEvangelicalismxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aPolitical culturexHistoryy21st centuryzUnited States. 0aRacexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aRacism against Black peoplezUnited States. 0aRacismxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aReligion and politicsxHistoryy21st centuryzUnited States. 0aWhite supremacy movementsxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Black Studies (Global).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027027?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027027423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027027/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles